# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: exhaust-manifold
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-cooling] In all cases, the air has to be cooler than the object or surface from which it is expected to remove heat.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-cooling] This is due to the second law of thermodynamics, which states that heat will only move spontaneously from a hot reservoir (the heat sink) to a cold reservoir (the air).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-cooling] When operating in an environment with lower air pressure like high altitude or airplane cabins, the cooling capacity has to be derated compared to that of sea level.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-cooling] A rule-of-thumb formula to note: 1 – (h/17500) = derating factor.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-cooling] Where *h* is the height over sea level in meters.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-cooling] And the result is the factor that should be multiplied with the cooling capacity in [W] to get the cooling capacity at the specified height over sea level.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] A particulate **air filter** is a device composed of fibrous or porous materials which removes particulates such as smoke, dust, pollen, mold, viruses, and bacteria from the air.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Filters containing an adsorbent or catalyst such as charcoal (carbon) or baking sodamay also remove odors and gaseous pollutants, such as volatile organic compounds or ozone.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Air filters are typically constructed of foam, pleated paper, cotton, or spun fiberglass.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Oil bath air filters have fallen out of favour aside from niche uses.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Air ionizers use a different method, static electric charge, than air filters to attract and remove dust particles but they may also be supplemented with an air filter.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] High efficiency particulate arrester (HEPA), originally called high-efficiency particulate absorber but also sometimes called high-efficiency particulate arresting or high-efficiency particulate arrestance, is a type of air filter.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Filters meeting the HEPA standard have many applications, including use in clean rooms for IC fabrication, medical facilities, automobiles, aircraft and homes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The filter must satisfy certain standards of efficiency such as those set by the United States Department of Energy (DOE).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Varying standards define what qualifies as a HEPA filter.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The two most common standards EN 1822 and ASME AG-1 require an air filter must remove (from the air that passes through) 99.95% (European Standard) or 99.97% (ASME standard) of particles that have a size greater than or equal to 0.3 μm.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The cabin air filter, also known in the United Kingdom as a pollen filter, is typically a pleated filter that is placed in the outside-air intake for the vehicle's passenger compartment.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Some of these filters are rectangular, while others are uniquely shaped to fit the available space of particular vehicles' outside-air intakes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The first automaker to include a disposable filter to keep the ventilation system clean was the Nash Motors "Weather Eye", introduced in 1940.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] A reusable heater core filter was available as an optional accessory on Studebaker models beginning in 1959, including Studebaker Lark automobiles (1959-1966), Studebaker Gran Turismo Hawk automobiles (1962-1964) and Studebaker Champ trucks (1960-1964).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The filter was an aluminum frame containing an aluminum mesh and was located directly above the heater core.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The filter was removed and installed from the engine compartment through a slot in the firewall.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] A long, thin rubber seal plugged the slot when the filter was installed.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The filter could be vacuumed and washed prior to installation.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Clogged or dirty cabin air filters can reduce airflow available to the cabin vents, as well as introduce allergens into the cabin air stream.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Since the cabin air temperature depends upon the flow rate of the air passing through the heater core, the evaporator, or both, clogged filters can greatly reduce the effectiveness and performance of the vehicle's air conditioning and heating systems.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] At the point of retail to the consumer, cabin air filter suppliers do not share performance testing characteristics listed below.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] However, some cabin air filter manufacturers do print a minimum efficiency reporting value (MERV) filter rating or cite N95 (however disclaim any NIOSH compliance) on their cabin air filter retail boxes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Pleat spacing (inversely pleat count) of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Airflow and pressure drop of air filter media is inversely proportional to filtration efficiency.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The combustion air filter prevents abrasive particulate matter from entering the engine's cylinders, causing mechanical wear, oil contamination, and change to emissions performance.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Many modern fuel injected vehicles use a pleated paper filter element in the form of a flat panel, usually placed inside a plastic box connected to the throttle body with duct work.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The overall unit (filter and housing, and duct work together) is called the **air cleaner**.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Air intake filter media technology improvements have helped increase overall efficiency of gas turbine air-compressors by using simulation tools to optimize aerodynamics and fluid dynamics.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Pleated paper filter elements are the nearly exclusive choice for automobile engine air cleaners, because they are efficient, easy to service, and cost-effective.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The "paper" term is somewhat misleading, as the paper filter media is constructed differently from papers used for writing or packaging, by employing binding resins or surface modifications.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The paper is pleated/bent in a zig-zag shape to increase the filtration surface area of the paper encountered by the airflow path, in the range of 50 times that of the air opening.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] There is a persistent belief among tuners, reinforced by advertising for aftermarket non-paper replacement filters manufacturers, that paper filters flow poorly enough to restrict engine performance.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Oil-wetted polyurethane foam elements are used in some aftermarket replacement automobile air filters.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Foam was in the past widely used in air cleaners on small engines on lawnmowers and other power equipment, but automotive-type paper filter elements have largely supplanted oil-wetted foam in these applications.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Foam filters are still commonly used on air compressors for air tools up to 5 horsepower (3.7 kW).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Due to the way dust is captured on foam filters, large amounts may be trapped without measurable change in airflow restriction.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Oiled cotton gauze is employed in a growing number of aftermarket automotive air filters marketed as high-performance items.[2] In the 1970's, with the introduction of the Fiat Abarth SS versions, cotton gauze air filters as OE automotive engine filters gained market traction.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Metal Mesh (stainless steel for rust resistance) is another example of an air filter media which can be ordered with different mesh counts to adjust for desired performance characteristics.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] An oil bath air cleaner consists of a sump containing a pool of oil and an insert which is filled with fiber, mesh, foam, or another coarse filter media.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The cleaner removes particles by adhering them to the oil-soaked filter media; as opposed to traditional filtration, the openings in the filter media are much larger than the particles that are to be filtered.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] When the cleaner is assembled, the media-containing body of the insert sits a short distance above the surface of the oil pool.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The rim of the insert overlaps the rim of the sump.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] This U-turn takes the air at high velocity across the surface of the oil pool.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Heavier (and typically larger) dust and dirt particles in the air cannot make the turn due to their inertia, so they fall into the oil and settle to the bottom of the base bowl.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Lighter (and typically smaller) particles stick to the filtration media in the insert, which is wetted by oil droplets aspirated there by normal airflow.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] The constant aspiration of oil onto the filter media slowly carries most of the finer trapped particles downward and the oil drips back into the reservoir where the particles accumulate.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Oil bath air cleaners were very widely used in automotive and small engine applications until the widespread industry adoption of the paper filter in the early 1960s.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Such cleaners are still used in off-road equipment where very high levels of dust are encountered, for oil bath air cleaners can sequester a great deal of dirt relative to their overall size without loss of filtration efficiency or airflow.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] In the early 20th century (about 1900 to 1930), water bath air cleaners were used in some applications (cars, trucks, tractors, and portable and stationary engines).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] They worked on roughly the same principles as oil bath air cleaners.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] For example, the original Fordson tractor had a water bath air cleaner.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] By the 1940s, oil bath designs had displaced water bath designs because of better filtering performance.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Bulk solids handling involves the transport of solids (mechanical transport, pneumatic transport) which may be in a powder form.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Many industries are handling bulk solids (mining industries, chemical industries, food industries) which requires the treatment of air streams escaping the process so that fine particles are not emitted, for regulatory reasons or economical reasons (loss of materials).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] As a consequence, air filters are positioned at many places in the process, especially at the reception of pneumatic conveying lines where the quantity of air is important and the load in fine particle quite important.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] Filters can also be placed at any point of air exchange in the process to avoid that pollutants enter the process, which is particularly true in pharmaceuticals and food industries.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-filter] European standard EN 779, on which the above table is based, remained in effect from 2012 to mid-2018, when it was replaced by ISO 16890.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:exhaust-manifold/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] An **airbox** is an empty chamber on the inlet of most combustion engines.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] It collects air from outside and feeds it to the intake hoses of each cylinder.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Older engines drew air directly from the surroundings into each individual carburetor.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Modern engines instead draw air into an airbox, which is connected by individual hoses to each carburetor or directly to the intake ports in fuel-injected engines, thus avoiding an extra intake manifold.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] The airbox allows the use of one air filter instead of multiples, reducing complexity.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Developments arising from concerns about engine emissions during the late 1970s allow the airbox to collect pump gases from the crankcase and the tank air vent and re-feed them to the engine.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Since the 1990s, engine designers also sought to exploit the properties of oscillating gas to improve performance.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Many high-performance motorcycles have the airbox fed from funnels in the front of the bike, where increased pressure forces more air into the intake and thus improves power.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Examples of this ram-air intake construction are the SRAD models of the Suzuki GSX-R750, the Kawasaki Ninja ZX-6R or the BMW S1000RR.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Secondly, designers exploit a property of air cavities known as Helmholtz resonance.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] Flow through the airbox is optimal at its resonance frequency, which depends on airbox volume and the inlet area and length of the snorkel.
[src:exhaust-manifold/airbox] The resonance is typically chosen to be at a medium speed where torque otherwise drops, caused by valve timing overlap.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] An **alternator** is a type of electric generator used in modern automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] As silicon-diode rectifiers became widely available and affordable, the alternator gradually replaced the dynamo.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] This was encouraged by the increasing electrical power required for cars in this period, with increasing loads from larger headlamps, electric wipers, heated rear windows, and other accessories.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The modern type of vehicle alternators were first used in military applications during World War II, to power radio equipment on specialist vehicles.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] After the war, other vehicles with high electrical demands — such as ambulances and radio taxis — could also be fitted with optional alternators.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Alternators were first introduced as standard equipment on a production car by the Chrysler Corporation on the Valiant in 1960, several years ahead of Ford and General Motors.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Some early automobiles, like the Ford Model T, used a different sort of charging system: an engine-driven magneto which generated low-voltage alternating current that was supplied to trembler coils, which provided the high voltage needed to generate ignition sparks.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The Model T incorporated its magneto into the engine flywheel.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The first Model Ts used the magneto solely for the trembler coil ignition.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Beginning with the 1915 model year, Ford added electric headlights, also powered by the magneto.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The magneto circuit was strictly AC, with no battery included.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] (There was a switch on the ignition coils to use a battery instead, which could be helpful when starting in cold weather, but Ford neither provided a battery nor did it encourage the use of one before it introduced an electric starter in 1919.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Starting in the 1919 model year, Ford upgraded the Model T to include an electric starter, which was standard for some models and optional for others.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] This starter installation also included a battery, charged by a conventional dynamo, and the lights were now powered by the battery.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] However, the flywheel magneto still powered the ignition, and since models without the starter had no battery, they continued to use magneto-powered lights.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Alternators have several advantages over direct-current generators (dynamos).
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] A set of rectifiers (diode bridge) is required to convert alternating current (AC) to DC.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] To provide direct current with low ripple, a polyphase winding is used and the pole-pieces of the rotor are shaped (claw-pole).
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators are usually belt-driven at 2–3 times crankshaft speed, speeds that could cause a commutator to fly apart in a generator.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The alternator runs at various RPM (which varies the frequency) since it is driven by the engine, regardless of direction of rotation.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] This is not a problem because the alternating current is rectified to DC.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Alternator regulators are also simpler than those for generators.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Generator regulators require a cutout relay to isolate the output coils (the armature) from the battery at low speed; that isolation is provided by the alternator rectifier diodes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Also, most generator regulators include a current limiter; alternators are inherently current-limited.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The claw pole design produces an AC waveform that is more efficiently rectified than a sine wave.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Despite their names, both 'DC generators' (or 'dynamos') and 'alternators' initially produce alternating current.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] In a so-called 'DC generator', this AC current is generated in the rotating armature, and then converted to DC by the commutator and brushes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] In an 'alternator', the AC current is generated in the stationary stator, and then is converted to DC by the rectifiers (diodes).
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger vehicle and light truck alternators use Lundahl or 'claw-pole' field construction.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] This uses a shaped iron core on the rotor to produce a multi-pole field from a single coil winding.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The poles of the rotor look like fingers of two hands interlocked with each other.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The coil is mounted axially inside this and field current is supplied by slip rings and carbon brushes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] These alternators have their field and stator windings cooled by axial airflow, produced by an external fan attached to the drive belt pulley.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Modern vehicles now use the compact alternator layout.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] This is electrically and magnetically similar, but has improved air cooling.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Better cooling permits more power from a smaller machine.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The casing has distinctive radial vent slots at each end and now encloses the fan.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Two fans are used, one at each end, and the airflow is semi-radial, entering axially and leaving radially outwards.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The stator windings now consist of a dense central band where the iron core and copper windings are tightly packed, and end bands where the windings are more exposed for better heat transfer.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The closer core spacing from the rotor improves magnetic efficiency.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The smaller, enclosed fans produce less noise, particularly at higher machine speeds.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Alternators can also be water-cooled in cars.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Larger vehicles may have field coil alternators similar to larger machines.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The windings of a 3 phase alternator may be connected using either the *delta* or *star* (*wye*) connection regime set-up.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Brushless versions of these type alternators are also common in larger machinery such as highway trucks and earthmoving machinery.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] With two oversized shaft bearings as the only wearing parts, these can provide extremely long and reliable service, even exceeding the engine overhaul intervals.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Automotive alternators require a voltage regulator which operates by modulating the small field current to produce a constant voltage at the battery terminals.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Early designs (c.1960s–1970s) used a discrete device mounted elsewhere in the vehicle.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Intermediate designs (c.1970s–1990s) incorporated the voltage regulator into the alternator housing.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Modern designs do away with the voltage regulator altogether; voltage regulation is now a function of the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The field current is much smaller than the output current of the alternator; for example, a 70 A alternator may need only 2-3 A of field current.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The field current is supplied to the rotor windings by slip rings.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The low current and relatively smooth slip rings ensure greater reliability and longer life than that obtained by a DC generator with its commutator and higher current being passed through its brushes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The field windings are supplied with power from the battery via the ignition switch and regulator.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] A parallel circuit supplies the "charge" warning indicator and is earthed via the regulator (which is why the indicator is on when the ignition is on but the engine is not running).
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Once the engine is running and the alternator is generating power, a diode feeds the field current from the alternator main output equalizing the voltage across the warning indicator which goes off.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The wire supplying the field current is often referred to as the "exciter" wire.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The drawback of this arrangement is that if the warning lamp burns out or the "exciter" wire is disconnected, no current reaches the field windings and the alternator will not generate power.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Some warning indicator circuits are equipped with a resistor in parallel with the lamp that permit excitation current to flow if the warning lamp burns out.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] The driver should check that the warning indicator is on when the engine is stopped; otherwise, there might not be any indication of a failure of the belt which may also drive the cooling water pump.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Some alternators will self-excite when the engine reaches a certain speed.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] In recent years, alternator regulators are linked to the vehicle's computer system and various factors including air temperature obtained from the intake air temperature sensor, battery temperature sensor and engine load are evaluated in adjusting the voltage supplied by the alternator.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Older automobiles with minimal lighting may have had an alternator capable of producing only 30 amperes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Typical passenger car and light truck alternators are rated around 50–70 A, though higher ratings are becoming more common, especially as there is more load on the vehicle's electrical system with air conditioning, electric power steering and other electrical systems.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators used on buses, heavy equipment or emergency vehicles may produce 300 A.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Semi-trucks usually have alternators which output 140 A.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Very large alternators may be water-cooled or oil-cooled.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Efficiency of automotive alternators is limited by fan cooling loss, bearing loss, iron loss, copper loss, and the voltage drop in the diode bridges.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Efficiency reduces dramatically at high speeds mainly due to fan resistance.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] At medium speeds efficiency of today's alternators is 70–80%.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] This betters very small high-performance permanent magnet alternators, such as those used for bicycle lighting systems, which achieve an efficiency around 60%.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Larger permanent magnet electric machines (that can operate as motors or alternators) can achieve today much higher efficiencies.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Pellegrino et al., for instance, propose not particularly expensive designs that show ample regions in which efficiency is above 96%.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Large AC generators used in power stations run at carefully controlled speeds and have no constraints on size or weight.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] They have very high efficiencies as high as 98%.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] Hybrid electric vehicles replace the separate alternator and starter motor with one or more combined motor/generator(s) that start the internal combustion engine, provide some or all of the mechanical power to the wheels, and charge a large storage battery.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] When more than one motor/generator is present, as in the Hybrid Synergy Drive used in the Toyota Prius and others, one may operate as a generator and feed the other as a motor, providing an electromechanical path for some of the engine power to flow to the wheels.
[src:exhaust-manifold/alternator-automotive] These motor/generators have considerably more powerful electronic devices for their control than the automotive alternator described above.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Varieties of American English include many patterns of pronunciation, vocabulary, grammar, and particularly spelling that are unified nationwide but distinct from other forms of English around the world.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] However, historical and present linguistic evidence does not support the notion of there being one single mainstream American accent.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The sound of American English continues to evolve, with some local accents disappearing, but several larger regional accents having emerged in the 20th century.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The use of English in the United States is a result of British colonization of the Americas.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The first wave of English-speaking settlers arrived in North America during the early 17th century, followed by further migrations in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] English thus predominated in the colonies even by the end of the 17th century's first immigration of non-English speakers from Western Europe and Africa.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Firsthand descriptions of a fairly uniform American English (particularly in contrast to the diverse regional dialects of British English) became common after the mid-18th century, while at the same time speakers' identification with this new variety increased.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Since the 18th century, American English has developed into some new varieties, including regional dialects that retain minor influences from waves of immigrant speakers of diverse languages, primarily European languages.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Some racial and regional variation in American English reflects these groups' patterns of geographic settlement, segregation, and resettlement.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] This can be seen, for example, in the influence of 18th-century Protestant Ulster Scots immigrants (known in the U.S. as the Scotch-Irish) in Appalachia developing Appalachian English and the 20th-century Great Migration bringing African-American Vernacular English to the Great Lakes urban centers.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Most American English accents fall under an umbrella known as General American.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Rather than one particular accent, General American is a spectrum of those American accents that Americans themselves do not associate with some particular region, ethnicity, or socioeconomic group.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] General American features are used most by Americans in formal contexts or who are highly educated.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Regional accents whose native features are perceived as General American include the accents of the North Midland (parts of the Midwest), Western New England, and the West.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The General American sound system's scope of influence and degree of expansion has been debated by linguists since the term was first used roughly a century ago.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Many late-20th and early-21st century studies are showing that it is gradually ousting the regional accents in urban areas of the South and the interior North, New York City, Philadelphia, and many other areas.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] It can generally be said that younger Americans are avoiding their traditional local features in favor of this more nationwide norm.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Furthermore, even General American itself appears to be evolving, with linguists identifying new features in speakers born since the last quarter of the 20th century, like a merger of the low-back vowels and a potentially related vowel shift, that are spreading across the nation.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Like many British accents, T glottalization is the norm in American accents, though only in particular environments (with *satin* pronounced [ˈsæʔn̩], not [ˈsætn̩]).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Specifically, the LOT–PALM merger is complete among most Americans and the LOT–THOUGHT merger among roughly half.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] A three-way LOT–PALM–THOUGHT merger is also very common, meaning that words like *baht*, *bot*, and *bought* are all homophones.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Most Americans pronounce the diphthong /aɪ/ before a voiceless consonant different from that same vowel before a voiced consonant: thus, in *price* and *bright* versus in *prize* and *bride*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] For many, outside the South, the first element of the diphthong is a higher and shorter vowel sound when in pre-voiceless position as opposed to pre-voiced position.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] All of these phenomena are explained in further detail under General American.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Unlike American accents, the traditional standard accent of (southern) England has evolved a *trap–bath* split.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Moreover, American accents preserve /h/ at the start of syllables, while perhaps a majority of the regional dialects of England participate in /h/ dropping, particularly in informal contexts.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The process of developing new lexical items began as soon as British English-speaking colonists in North America began borrowing names for unfamiliar flora, fauna, and topography from the Native American languages.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Examples of such names are *opossum, raccoon, squash*, *moose* (from Algonquian), *wigwam*, and *moccasin*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] American English speakers have integrated traditionally non-English terms and expressions into the mainstream cultural lexicon; for instance, *en masse*, from French; *cookie*, from Dutch; *kindergarten* from German, and *rodeo* from Spanish.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Landscape features are often loanwords from French or Spanish, and the word *corn*, used in England to refer to wheat (or any cereal), came to denote the maize plant, the most important crop in the U.S.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Other common differences between UK and American English include: *aerial* (UK) vs.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] *apartment*, *fringe* (UK; for hair hanging over the forehead) vs.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Most Mexican Spanish contributions came after the War of 1812, with the opening of the West, like *ranch* (now a common house style).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Due to Mexican culinary influence, many Spanish words are incorporated in general use when talking about certain popular dishes: cilantro (instead of coriander), queso, tacos, quesadillas, enchiladas, tostadas, fajitas, burritos, and guacamole.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] These words usually lack an English equivalent and are found in popular restaurants.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] New forms of dwelling created new terms *(lot, waterfront)* and types of homes like *log cabin, adobe* in the 18th century; *apartment, shanty* in the 19th century; *project, condominium, townhouse, mobile home* in the 20th century; and parts thereof *(driveway, breezeway, backyard)*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Already existing English words—such as *store, shop, lumber*—underwent shifts in meaning; others remained in the U.S. while changing in Britain.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Science, urbanization, and democracy have been important factors in bringing about changes in the written and spoken language of the United States.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] From the world of business and finance came new terms (*merger, downsize, bottom line*), from sports and gambling terminology came, specific jargon aside, common everyday American idioms, including many idioms related to baseball.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The names of some American inventions remained largely confined to North America (*elevator* [except in the aeronautical sense], *gasoline*) as did certain automotive terms (*truck*, *trunk*).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] New foreign loanwords came with 19th and early 20th century European immigration to the U.S.; notably, from Yiddish *(chutzpah, schmooze, bupkis, glitch*) and German (*hamburger, wiener*).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] American English has always shown a marked tendency to use words in different parts of speech and nouns are often used as verbs.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Examples of nouns that are now also verbs are *interview, advocate, vacuum, lobby, pressure, rear-end, transition, feature, profile, hashtag, head, divorce, loan, estimate, X-ray, spearhead, skyrocket, showcase, bad-mouth, vacation, major,* and many others.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Compounds coined in the U.S. are for instance *foothill, landslide* (in all senses), *backdrop, teenager,* *brainstorm, bandwagon, hitchhike, smalltime,* and a huge number of others.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Other compound words have been founded based on industrialization and the wave of the automobile: five-passenger car, four-door sedan, two-door sedan, and station-wagon (called an estate car in British English).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Some are euphemistic *(human resources, affirmative action, correctional facility).* Many compound nouns have the verb-and-preposition combination: *stopover, lineup, tryout, spin-off, shootout, holdup, hideout, comeback, makeover,* and many more.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Some prepositional and phrasal verbs are in fact of American origin (*win out, hold up, back up/off/down/out, face up to* and many others).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Noun endings such as *-ee (retiree), -ery (bakery), -ster (gangster)* and *-cian (beautician)* are also particularly productive in the U.S.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] A number of words and meanings that originated in Middle English or Early Modern English and that have been in everyday use in the United States have since disappeared in most varieties of British English; some of these have cognates in Lowland Scots.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Terms such as *fall* ("autumn"), *faucet* ("tap"), *diaper* ("nappy"; itself unused in the U.S.), *candy* ("sweets"), *skillet*, *eyeglasses*, and *obligate* are often regarded as Americanisms.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] *Fall*, however, came to denote the season in 16th century England, a contraction of Middle English expressions like "fall of the leaf" and "fall of the year".
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] *Gotten* (past participle of *get*) is often considered to be largely an Americanism.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Other words and meanings were brought back to Britain from the U.S., especially in the second half of the 20th century; these include *hire* ("to employ"), *I guess* (famously criticized by H.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Fowler), *baggage*, *hit* (a place), and the adverbs *overly* and *presently* ("currently").
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Some of these, for example, *monkey wrench* and *wastebasket*, originated in 19th century Britain.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The adjectives *mad* meaning "angry", *smart* meaning "intelligent", and *sick* meaning "ill" are also more frequent in American (and Irish) English than British English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Linguist Bert Vaux created a survey, completed in 2003, polling English speakers across the United States about their specific everyday word choices, hoping to identify regionalisms.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] American English and British English (BrE) differ in relatively minor ways in their grammar and writing conventions.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The first large American dictionary, *An American Dictionary of the English Language*, known as Webster's Dictionary, was written by Noah Webster in 1828, codifying several of these spellings.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Often, these differences are a matter of relative preferences rather than absolute rules; and most are not stable since the two varieties are constantly influencing each other, and American English is not a standardized set of dialects.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Differences in orthography are also minor.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The main differences are that American English usually uses spellings such as *flavor* for British *flavour*, *fiber* for *fibre*, *defense* for *defence*, *analyze* for *analyse*, *license* for *licence*, *catalog* for *catalogue* and *traveling* for *travelling*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Noah Webster popularized such spellings in America, but he did not invent most of them.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] AmE almost always uses *-ize* in words like *realize*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] BrE prefers *-ise*, but also uses *-ize* on occasion (see: Oxford spelling).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] There are a few differences in punctuation rules.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] British English is more tolerant of run-on sentences, called "comma splices" in American English, and American English prefers that periods and commas be placed inside closing quotation marks even in cases in which British rules would place them outside.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] American English also favors the double quotation mark ("like this") over the single ('as here').
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] AmE sometimes favors words that are morphologically more complex, whereas BrE uses clipped forms, such as AmE *transportation* and BrE *transport* or where the British form is a back-formation, such as AmE *burglarize* and BrE *burgle* (from *burglar*).
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] However, while individuals usually use one or the other, both forms will be widely understood and mostly used alongside each other within the two systems.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] as well as the related Telsur Project's regional maps.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Any region may also contain speakers of a "General American" accent that resists the marked features of their region.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The regional sounds of present-day American English are reportedly engaged in a complex phenomenon of "both convergence and divergence": some accents are homogenizing and leveling, while others are diversifying and deviating further away from one another.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] As of the 20th century, the middle and eastern Great Lakes area, Chicago being the largest city with these speakers, also ushered in certain unique features, including the fronting of the LOT /ɑ/ vowel in the mouth toward [a] and tensing of the TRAP /æ/ vowel wholesale to [eə].
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] These sound changes have triggered a series of other vowel shifts in the same region, known by linguists as the "Inland North".
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The Inland North shares with the Eastern New England dialect (including Boston accents) a backer tongue positioning of the GOOSE /u/ vowel (to [u]) and the MOUTH /aʊ/ vowel (to [ɑʊ~äʊ]) in comparison to the rest of the country.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Ranging from northern New England across the Great Lakes to Minnesota, another Northern regional marker is the variable fronting of /ɑ/ before /r/, for example, appearing four times in the stereotypical Boston shibboleth *Park the car in Harvard Yard*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Several other phenomena serve to distinguish regional American accents.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Boston, Pittsburgh, Upper Midwestern, and Western U.S. accents have fully completed a merger of the LOT vowel with the THOUGHT vowel (/ɑ/ and /ɔ/, respectively): a *cot–caught* merger, which is rapidly spreading throughout the whole country.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] However, the South, Inland North, and a Northeastern coastal corridor passing through Rhode Island, New York City, Philadelphia, and Baltimore typically preserve an older *cot–caught* distinction.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] For that Northeastern corridor, the realization of the THOUGHT vowel is particularly marked, as depicted in humorous spellings, like in *tawk* and *cawfee* (*talk* and *coffee*), which intend to represent it being tense and diphthongal: [oə].
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] A split of TRAP into two separate phonemes, using different *a* pronunciations for example in *gap* [æ] versus *gas* [eə], further defines New York City as well as Philadelphia–Baltimore accents.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Most Americans preserve all historical /r/ sounds, using what is known as a rhotic accent.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Non-rhoticity makes a word like *car* sound like *cah* or *source* like *sauce*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] New York City and Southern accents are the most widely recognized regional accents in the country, as well as the most stigmatized and socially disfavored.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The fronting of the vowels of GOOSE, GOAT, MOUTH, and STRUT tends to also define Southern accents as well as the accents spoken in the "Midland": a vast band of the country that constitutes an intermediate dialect region between the traditional North and South.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Western U.S. accents mostly fall under the General American spectrum.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Although no longer region-specific, African-American Vernacular English, which remains the native variety of most working- and middle-class African Americans, has a close relationship to Southern dialects and has greatly influenced everyday speech of many Americans, including hip hop culture.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Hispanic and Latino Americans have also developed native-speaker varieties of English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The best-studied Latino Englishes are Chicano English, spoken in the West and Midwest, and New York Latino English, spoken in the New York metropolitan area.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Additionally, ethnic varieties such as Yeshiva English and "Yinglish" are spoken by some American Orthodox Jews, Cajun Vernacular English by some Cajuns in southern Louisiana, and Pennsylvania Dutch English by some Pennsylvania Dutch people.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] American Indian Englishes have been documented among diverse Indian tribes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] The island state of Hawaii, though primarily English-speaking, is also home to a creole language known commonly as Hawaiian Pidgin, and some Hawaii residents speak English with a Pidgin-influenced accent.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] In 2024, about 247.7 million Americans, aged five or above, spoke English at home, a majority (77%) of the total U.S. population aged five and over.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Of the 50 states, 32 have adopted legislation granting official (or co-official) status to English within their jurisdictions, in some cases as part of what has been called the English-only movement.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Typically only "English" is specified, not a particular variety like American English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/american-english] Puerto Rico is the only United States territory in which another language – Spanish – is the common language at home, in public, and in government.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English began to diverge from British and Hiberno-English after the First Fleet established the Colony of New South Wales in 1788.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English arose from a dialectal melting pot created by the intermingling of early settlers who were from a variety of dialectal regions of Great Britain and Ireland, though its most significant influences were the dialects of Southern England.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] By the 1820s, the native-born colonists' speech was recognisably distinct from speakers in Britain and Ireland.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English differs from other varieties in its phonology, pronunciation, lexicon, idiom, grammar and spelling.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English is relatively consistent across the continent, although it encompasses numerous regional and sociocultural varieties.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] "General Australian" describes the *de facto* standard dialect, which is perceived to be free of pronounced regional or sociocultural markers and is often used in the media.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Similar to early American English, Australian English passed through a process of extensive dialect levelling and mixing which produced a relatively homogeneous new variety of English which was easily understood by all.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The earliest Australian English was spoken by the first generation of native-born colonists in the Colony of New South Wales from the end of the 18th century.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] These native-born children were exposed to a wide range of dialects from across the British Isles.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The dialects of Southern England, including most notably the traditional Cockney dialect of London, were particularly influential on the development of the new variety and constituted "the major input of the various sounds that went into constructing" Australian English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] All the other regions of England were represented among the early colonists.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] A large proportion of early convicts and colonists were from Ireland (comprising 25% of the total convict population), and many of them spoke Irish as a sole or first language.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] They were joined by other non-native speakers of English from the Scottish Highlands and Wales.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Peter Miller Cunningham's 1827 book *Two Years in New South Wales* described the distinctive accent and vocabulary that had developed among the native-born colonists.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The first of the Australian gold rushes in the 1850s began a large wave of immigration, during which about two percent of the population of the United Kingdom emigrated to the colonies of New South Wales and Victoria.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The Gold Rushes brought immigrants and linguistic influences from many parts of the world.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] An example was the introduction of vocabulary from American English, including some terms later considered to be typically Australian, such as *bushwhacker* and *squatter*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The most obvious way in which Australian English is distinctive from other varieties of English is through its unique pronunciation.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] It shares most similarity with New Zealand English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Like most dialects of English, it is distinguished primarily by the phonetic quality of its vowels.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The vowels of Australian English can be divided according to length.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The long vowels, which include monophthongs and diphthongs, mostly correspond to the tense vowels used in analyses of Received Pronunciation (RP) as well as its centring diphthongs.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The short vowels, consisting only of monophthongs, correspond to the RP lax vowels.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] There exist pairs of long and short vowels with overlapping vowel quality giving Australian English phonemic length distinction, which is also present in some regional south-eastern dialects of the UK and eastern seaboard dialects in the US.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] An example of this feature is the distinction between *ferry* /ˈfeɹiː/ and *fairy* /ˈfeːɹiː/.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] As with New Zealand English and General American English, the weak-vowel merger is complete in Australian English: unstressed /ɪ/ is merged into /ə/ (schwa), unless it is followed by a velar consonant.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Examples of this feature are the following pairings, which are pronounced identically in Australian English: *Rosa's* and *roses*, as well as *Lennon* and *Lenin*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Other examples are the following pairs, which rhyme in Australian English: *abbott* with *rabbit*, and *dig it* with *bigot*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Most varieties of Australian English exhibit only a partial trap-bath split.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The words *bath*, *grass* and *can't* are always pronounced with the "long" /ɐː/ of *father*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Throughout the majority of the country, the "flat" /æ/ of *man* is the dominant pronunciation for the *a* vowel in the following words: *dance*, *advance*, *plant*, *example* and *answer*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The exception is the state of South Australia, where a more advanced trap-bath split is found, and where the dominant pronunciation of all the preceding words incorporates the "long" /ɐː/ of *father*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] There is little variation in the sets of consonants used in different English dialects but there are variations in how these consonants are used.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English is uniformly non-rhotic; that is, the /ɹ/ sound does not appear at the end of a syllable or immediately before a consonant.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] As with many non-rhotic dialects, linking /ɹ/ can occur when a word that has a final ⟨r⟩ in the spelling comes before another word that starts with a vowel.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] An intrusive /ɹ/ may similarly be inserted before a vowel in words that do not have ⟨r⟩ in the spelling in certain environments, namely after the long vowel /oː/ and after word final /ə/.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] This can be heard in "law-r-and order", where an intrusive R is voiced between the AW and the A.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] As with North American English, intervocalic alveolar flapping is a feature of Australian English: prevocalic /t/ and /d/ surface as the alveolar tap [ɾ] after sonorants other than /m, ŋ/ as well as at the end of a word or morpheme before any vowel in the same breath group.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Examples of this feature are that the following pairs are pronounced similarly or identically: *latter* and *ladder*, as well as *rated* and *raided*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In common with most varieties of Scottish English and American English, the phoneme /l/ is pronounced by Australians as a "dark" (velarised) *l* ([ɫ]) in almost all positions, unlike other dialects such as Received Pronunciation, Hiberno (Irish) English, etc.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Differences in stress, weak forms and standard pronunciation of isolated words occur between Australian English and other forms of English, which while noticeable do not impair intelligibility.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The affixes *-ary*, *-ery*, *-ory*, *-bury*, *-berry* and *-mony* (seen in words such as *necessary, mulberry* and *matrimony*) can be pronounced either with a full vowel (/ˈnesəseɹiː, ˈmalbeɹiː, ˈmætɹəməʉniː/) or a schwa (/ˈnesəsəɹiː, ˈmalbəɹiː, ˈmætɹəməniː/).
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Although some words like *necessary* are almost universally pronounced with the full vowel, older generations of Australians are relatively likely to pronounce these affixes with a schwa as is typical in British English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Meanwhile, younger generations are relatively likely to use a full vowel.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Words ending in unstressed *-ile* derived from Latin adjectives ending in *-ilis* are pronounced with a full vowel, so that *fertile* /ˈfɜːtɑel/ sounds like *fur tile* rather than rhyming with *turtle* /ˈtɜːtəl/.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In addition, miscellaneous pronunciation differences exist when compared with other varieties of English in relation to various isolated words, with some of those pronunciations being unique to Australian English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Relative to many other national dialect groupings, Australian English is relatively homogeneous across the country.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Some relatively minor regional differences in pronunciation exist.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] A limited range of word choices is strongly regional in nature.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Consequently, the geographical background of individuals may be inferred if they use words that are peculiar to particular Australian states or territories and, in some cases, even smaller regions.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In addition, some Australians speak creole languages derived from Australian English, such as Australian Kriol, Torres Strait Creole and Norfuk.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Academic research has also identified notable sociocultural variation within Australian English, which is mostly evident in phonology.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Although Australian English is relatively homogeneous, there are some regional variations.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The dialects of English spoken in the various states and territories of Australia differ slightly in vocabulary and phonology.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Most regional differences are in word usage.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Swimming clothes are known as *cossies*, /ˈkɔziːz/ *togs* or *swimmers* in New South Wales, *togs* in Queensland, and *bathers* in Victoria, Tasmania, Western Australia and South Australia.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] What Queensland calls a *stroller* is usually called a *pram* in Victoria, Western Australia, South Australia, New South Wales, and Tasmania.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Preference for some synonymous words also differ between states.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] *Garbage* (i.e., garbage bin, garbage truck) dominates over *rubbish* in New South Wales and Queensland, while *rubbish* is more popular in Victoria, Tasmania, Western Australia and South Australia.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Additionally, the word *footy* generally refers to the most popular football code in an area; that is, rugby league or rugby union depending on the local area, in most of New South Wales and Queensland.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] More commonly *rugby* is used to distinguish rugby union from *footy* which refers to the more popular rugby league.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] *Footy* commonly is used for Australian rules football elsewhere however the term refers to the both prominent codes, rugby league and Australian rules football, interchangeably, depending on context of usage outside of regional perrameters.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In some pockets of Melbourne & Western Sydney *football* and more rarely *footy* will refer to association football although unlike more common international terminology, Australian English uses the term *soccer* and not *football* or *footy*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Beer glasses are also named differently in different states.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Distinctive grammatical patterns exist such as the use of the interrogative *eh* (also spelled *ay* or *aye*), which is particularly associated with Queensland.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] *Secret Santa* () and *Kris Kringle* are used in all states, with the former being more common in Queensland.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The most pronounced variation in phonology is between South Australia and the other states and territories.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The trap–bath split is more complete in South Australia, in contrast to the other states.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Accordingly, words such as *dance*, *advance*, *plant*, *example* and *answer* are pronounced with /ɐː/ (as in *father*) far more frequently in South Australia while the older /æ/ (as in *mad*) is dominant elsewhere in Australia.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] *L*-vocalisation is also more common in South Australia than other states.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In Western Australian and Queensland English, the vowels in *near* and *square* are typically realised as centring diphthongs ([nɪə, skweə]), whereas in the other states they may also be realised as monophthongs: [nɪː, skweː].
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] A feature common in Victorian English is salary–celery merger, whereby a Victorian pronunciation of *Ellen* may sound like *Alan* and Victoria's capital city *Melbourne* may sound like *Malbourne* to speakers from other states.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] There is also regional variation in /ʉː/ before /l/ (as in *school* and *pool*).
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In some parts of Australia, notably Victoria, a fully backed allophone of /ʉː/, transcribed [ʊː], is common before /l/.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] As a result, the pairs full/fool and pull/pool differ phonetically only in vowel length for those speakers.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The usual allophone for /ʉː/ is further forward in Queensland and New South Wales than Victoria.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] A *final particle but*, where "but" is the concluding word in a sentence, has also evolved as a distinctive feature in Australian English, particularly in Western Australia and Queensland.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In conversational Australian English it is thought to be a turn-yielding particle that marks contrastive content in the utterance it closes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] It is a linguistic trait sometimes employed in Australian literature to indicate that the character is quintessentially Australian.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The General Australian accent serves as the standard variety of English across the country.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] According to linguists, it emerged during the 19th century.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] General Australian is the dominant variety across the continent, and is particularly so in urban areas.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The increasing dominance of General Australian reflects its prominence on radio and television since the latter half of the 20th century.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Recent generations have seen a comparatively smaller proportion of the population speaking with the *Broad* sociocultural variant, which differs from General Australian in its phonology.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The Broad variant is found across the continent and is relatively more prominent in rural and outer-suburban areas.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] A largely historical *Cultivated* sociocultural variant, which adopted features of British Received Pronunciation and which was commonplace in official media during the early 20th century, had become largely extinct by the onset of the 21st century.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian Aboriginal English is made up of a range of forms which developed differently in different parts of Australia, and are said to vary along a continuum, from forms close to Standard Australian English to more non-standard forms.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] There are distinctive features of accent, grammar, words and meanings, as well as language use.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Academics have noted the emergence of numerous ethnocultural dialects of Australian English that are spoken by people from some minority non-English speaking backgrounds.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] These ethnocultural varieties contain features of General Australian English as adopted by the children of immigrants blended with some non-English language features, such as Afro-Asiatic languages and languages of Asia.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Samoan English is also influencing Australian English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Other ethnolects include those of Lebanese and Vietnamese Australians.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] A high rising terminal in Australian English was noted and studied earlier than in other varieties of English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The feature is sometimes called *Australian questioning intonation*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Research published in 1986, regarding vernacular speech in Sydney, suggested that high rising terminal was initially spread by young people in the 1960s.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] It found that the high rising terminal was used more than twice as often by young people than older people, and is more common among women than men.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In the United Kingdom, it has occasionally been considered one of the variety's stereotypical features, and its spread there is attributed to the popularity of Australian soap operas.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English has many words and idioms which are unique to the dialect.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Internationally well-known examples of Australian terminology include *outback*, meaning a remote, sparsely populated area, *the bush*, meaning either a native forest or a country area in general, and *g'day*, a greeting.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] *Dinkum*, or *fair dinkum* means "true", "legitimate" or "is that true?", among other things, depending on context and inflection.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The derivative *dinky-di* means "true" or devoted: a "dinky-di Aussie" is a "true Australian".
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian poetry, such as "The Man from Snowy River", as well as folk songs such as "Waltzing Matilda", contain many historical Australian words and phrases that are understood by Australians even though some are not in common usage today.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English, in common with British English, uses the word *mate* to mean *friend*, as well as the word *bloody* as a mild expletive or intensifier.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] "Mate" is also used in multiple ways including to indicate "mateship" or formally call out the target of a threat or insult, depending on intonation and context.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Several words used by Australians were at one time used in the UK but have since fallen out of usage or changed in meaning there.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Some elements of Aboriginal languages have been adopted by Australian English—mainly as names for places, flora and fauna (for example dingo) and local culture.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Many such are localised, and do not form part of general Australian use, while others, such as *kangaroo*, *boomerang*, *budgerigar*, *wallaby* and so on have become international.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Other examples are *cooee* and *hard yakka*.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The former is used as a high-pitched call, for attracting attention, (pronounced /ˈkʉːiː/) which travels long distances.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] *Cooee* is also a notional distance: "if he's within *cooee*, we'll spot him".
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] *Hard yakka* means "hard work" and is derived from *yakka*, from the Jagera/Yagara language once spoken in the Brisbane region.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The word *bung*, meaning "dead" was originally a Yagara word which was used in the pidgin widely spoken across Australia.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Many towns or suburbs of Australia have also been influenced or named after Aboriginal words.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The best-known example is the capital, Canberra, named after a local Ngunnawal language word thought to mean "women's breasts" or "meeting place".
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Litotes, such as "not bad", "not much" and "you're not wrong", are also used.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Diminutives and hypocorisms are common and are often used to indicate familiarity.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Some common examples are *arvo* (afternoon), *barbie* (barbecue), *smoko* (cigarette break), *Aussie* (Australian) and *Straya* (Australia).
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] This may also be done with people's names to create nicknames (other English speaking countries create similar diminutives).
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] For example, "Gazza" from Gary, or "Smitty" from John Smith.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The use of the suffix *-o* originates in Irish: *ó*, which is both a postclitic and a suffix with much the same meaning as in Australian English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] In informal speech, incomplete comparisons are sometimes used, such as "sweet as" (as in "That car is sweet as.").
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] "Full", "fully" or "heaps" may precede a word to act as an intensifier (as in "The waves at the beach were heaps good.").
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] This was more common in regional Australia and South Australia but has been in common usage in urban Australia for decades.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] The suffix "-ly" is sometimes omitted in broader Australian English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] For instance, "really good" can become "real good".
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australia's switch to the metric system in the 1970s changed most of the country's vocabulary of measurement from imperial to metric measures.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Since the switch to metric, heights of people are listed in centimetres on official documents and distances by road on signs are listed in terms of kilometres and metres.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] There are extensive terms used in other varieties of English which are not widely used in Australian English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] These terms usually do not result in Australian English speakers failing to comprehend speakers of other varieties of English, as Australian English speakers will often be familiar with such terms through exposure to media or may ascertain the meaning using context.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English has influenced several other varieties of English, particularly in Oceania, and other languages spoken in Australia and Oceania.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] Australian English has been a heavy source of vocabulary for both English and French (plus in turn local languages) in New Caledonia, with a large amount of Australianised Anglicisms being present in New Caledonian speech.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p01] For example, the Australian agricultural terms *paddock*, *run*, *station*, *stock*, *stockman*, *stockwhip* and *stockyard* are all used in New Caledonia.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] The general rules which apply to Australian English are described at English grammar.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Grammatical differences between varieties of English are minor relative to differences in phonology and vocabulary and do not generally affect intelligibility.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] As in all English-speaking countries, there is no central authority that prescribes official usage with respect to matters of spelling, grammar, punctuation or style.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] There are several dictionaries of Australian English which adopt a descriptive approach.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] The *Macquarie Dictionary* and the *Australian Oxford Dictionary* are most commonly used by universities, governments and courts as the standard for Australian English spelling.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Australian spelling is significantly closer to British compared with American spelling, as it did not adopt the systematic reforms promulgated in Noah Webster's 1828 Dictionary.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Notwithstanding, the Macquarie Dictionary often lists most American spellings as acceptable secondary variants.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Unspaced forms such as *onto*, *anytime*, *alright* and *anymore* are also listed as being equally as acceptable as their spaced counterparts.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Additionally, the spellings *donut* and *percent* as opposed to *doughnut* and *per cent* have become more common than their counterparts; however, the official Australian style manual considers *percent* to be a misspelling.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] There is variation between and within varieties of English in the treatment of **-t** and **-ed** endings for past tense verbs.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] The Macquarie Dictionary does not favour either, but it suggests that *leap**ed***, *lean**ed*** or *learn**ed*** (with **-ed** endings) are more common but *spel**t*** and *burn**t*** (with **-t** endings) are more common.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Different spellings have existed throughout Australia's history.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] What are today regarded as American spellings were popular in Australia throughout the late 19th and early 20th centuries, with the Victorian Department of Education endorsing them into the 1970s and *The Age* newspaper until the 1990s.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] This influence can be seen in the spelling of the Australian Labor Party and also in some place names such as Victor Harbor.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] The *Concise Oxford English Dictionary* has been credited with re-establishing the dominance of the British spellings in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] For a short time during the late 20th century, Harry Lindgren's 1969 spelling reform proposal (Spelling Reform 1 or SR1) gained some support in Australia and was adopted by the Australian Teachers' Federation and minister Doug Everingham in personal correspondence.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] A prominent style guide for the Government of Australia is the *Australian Government Style Manual.* It is a comprehensive guide that includes usage guides on grammar, punctuation, and conventions for government writers and editors.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] To indicate speech, both single and double inverted comma quotation marks are used.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Generally, double quotation marks are preferred for use in the first instance, with single quotation marks used for quotes within quotes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] However, the opposite is true in the government and corporate sectors, where double quotation marks are reserved for quotes within quotes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] The punctuation mark used to end a sentence is called a full stop; a period usually refers to menstruation or an interval of time.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] The DD/MM/YYYY date format is followed and the 12-hour clock is generally used in everyday life (the 24-hour clock is used by the military and police, and for transport timetables).
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] The country has used the metric system since the 1970s, though the imperial system is still sometimes used informally, especially among older Australians, in idioms (e.g. to "go the extra mile", not "go the extra kilometre") and in reference to a person's height.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] In betting, decimal odds are used in preference to fractional odds, as used in the United Kingdom, or moneyline odds in the United States.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] There are two major English language keyboard layouts, the United States layout and the United Kingdom layout.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Keyboards and keyboard software for the Australian market universally uses the US keyboard layout, which lacks the pound (£), euro and negation symbols and uses a different layout for punctuation symbols from the UK keyboard layout.
[src:exhaust-manifold/australian-english-p02] Percentage of people who speak another language at home who are fluent in English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] In automotive engineering, an **exhaust manifold** collects the exhaust gases from multiple cylinders into one pipe.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The word *manifold* comes from the Old English word *manigfeald* (from the Anglo-Saxon *manig* [many] and *feald* [fold]) and refers to the folding together of multiple inputs and outputs (in contrast, an inlet or intake manifold *supplies* air *to* the cylinders).
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Exhaust manifolds are generally simple cast iron or stainless steel units which collect engine exhaust gas from multiple cylinders and deliver it to the exhaust pipe.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] For many engines, there are aftermarket tubular exhaust manifolds known as **headers** in American English, as extractor manifolds in British and Australian English, and simply as "tubular manifolds" in British English.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] These consist of individual exhaust headpipes for each cylinder, which then usually converge into one tube called a collector.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Headers that do not have collectors are called zoomie headers.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The most common types of aftermarket headers are made of mild steel or stainless steel tubing for the primary tubes along with flat flanges and possibly a larger diameter collector made of a similar material as the primaries.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] They may be coated with a ceramic-type finish (sometimes both inside and outside), or painted with a heat-resistant finish, or bare.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Chrome plated headers are available but these tend to blue after use.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Polished stainless steel will also color (usually a yellow tint), but less than chrome in most cases.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Another form of modification used is to insulate a standard or aftermarket manifold.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This decreases the amount of heat given off into the engine bay, therefore reducing the intake manifold temperature.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The goal of performance exhaust headers is mainly to decrease flow resistance (back pressure), and to increase the volumetric efficiency of an engine, resulting in a gain in power output.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The processes occurring can be explained by the gas laws, specifically the ideal gas law and the combined gas law.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] When an engine starts its exhaust stroke, the piston moves up the cylinder bore, decreasing the total chamber volume.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] As the exhaust gases equalize between the combustion chamber and the atmosphere, the difference in pressure decreases and the exhaust velocity decreases.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The remaining exhaust gas forms the low-pressure *tail* component.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This tail component may initially match ambient atmospheric pressure, but the momentum of the high and medium-pressure components reduces the pressure in the combustion chamber to a lower-than-atmospheric level.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This relatively low pressure helps to extract all the combustion products from the cylinder and induct the intake charge during the overlap period when both intake and exhaust valves are partially open.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Length, cross-sectional area, and shaping of the exhaust ports and pipeworks influences the degree of scavenging effect, and the engine speed range over which scavenging occurs.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The magnitude of the exhaust scavenging effect is a direct function of the velocity of the high and medium pressure components of the exhaust pulse.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Performance headers work to increase the exhaust velocity as much as possible.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] One technique is tuned-length primary tubes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This technique attempts to time the occurrence of each exhaust pulse, to occur one after the other in succession while still in the exhaust system.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The lower pressure tail of an exhaust pulse then serves to create a greater pressure difference between the high pressure head of the next exhaust pulse, thus increasing the velocity of that exhaust pulse.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] In V6 and V8 engines where there is more than one exhaust bank, "Y-pipes" and "X-pipes" work on the same principle of using the low pressure component of an exhaust pulse to increase the velocity of the next exhaust pulse.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Great care must be used when selecting the length and diameter of the primary tubes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Tubes that are too large will cause the exhaust gas to expand and slow down, decreasing the scavenging effect.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Tubes that are too small will create exhaust flow resistance which the engine must work to expel the exhaust gas from the chamber, reducing power and leaving exhaust in the chamber to dilute the incoming intake charge.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Since engines produce more exhaust gas at higher speeds, the header(s) are tuned to a particular engine speed range according to the intended application.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Typically, wide primary tubes offer the best gains in power and torque at higher engine speeds, while narrow tubes offer the best gains at lower speeds.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Many headers are also resonance tuned, to utilize the low-pressure reflected wave rarefaction pulse which can help scavenging the combustion chamber during valve overlap.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This pulse is created in all exhaust systems each time a change in density occurs, such as when exhaust merges into the collector.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] For clarification, the rarefaction pulse is the technical term for the same process that was described above in the "head, body, tail" description.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] By tuning the length of the primary tubes, usually by means of resonance tuning, the rarefaction pulse can be timed to coincide with the exact moment valve overlap occurs.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Typically, long primary tubes resonate at a lower engine speed than short primary tubes.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Crossplane V8 engines have a left and right bank each containing 4 cylinders.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] When the engine is running, pistons are firing according to the engine firing order.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] If a bank has two consecutive piston firings it will create a high pressure area in the exhaust pipe, because two exhaust pulses are moving through it close in time.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] As the two pulses move in the exhaust pipe they should encounter either an X or H pipe.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] When they encounter the pipe, part of the pulse diverts into the X-H pipe which lowers the total pressure by a small amount.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] The reason for this decrease in pressure is that the fluid (liquid, air or gas) will travel along a pipe and when it comes at a crossing the fluid will take the path of least resistance and some will bleed off, thus lowering the pressure slightly.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Without an X-H pipe the flow of exhaust would be jerky or inconsistent, and the engine would not run at its highest efficiency.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Today's understanding of exhaust systems and fluid dynamics has given rise to a number of mechanical improvements.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] One such improvement can be seen in the exhaust ultimate power valve ("EXUP") fitted to some Yamaha motorcycles.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] It constantly adjusts the back pressure within the collector of the exhaust system to enhance pressure wave formation as a function of engine speed.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This ensures good low to mid-range performance.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] At low engine speeds the wave pressure within the pipe network is low.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] A full oscillation of the Helmholtz resonance occurs before the exhaust valve is closed, and to increase low-speed torque, large amplitude exhaust pressure waves are artificially induced.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This is achieved by partial closing of an internal valve within the exhaust—the EXUP valve—at the point where the four primary pipes from the cylinders join.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This junction point essentially behaves as an artificial atmosphere, hence the alteration of the pressure at this point controls the behavior of reflected waves at this sudden increase in area discontinuity.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] Closing the valve increases the local pressure, thus inducing the formation of larger amplitude negative reflected expansion waves.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] This enhances low speed torque up to a speed at which the loss due to increased back pressure outweighs the EXUP tuning effect.
[src:exhaust-manifold/exhaust-manifold] At higher speeds the EXUP valve is fully opened and the exhaust is allowed to flow freely.
